# Class: obo:GENEPIO_0001900 (set)

AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label obo:GENEPIO_0001900 "set"@en)

# Class: obo:GENEPIO_0001901 (ordered set)

AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:comment obo:GENEPIO_0001901 "This data type is for items that have a unique order or rank with respect to each other in a set BUT NO meaningful DISTANCE metric exists between items aside from their position in the full set.  \"Favorite soft drinks\" or \"Favorite colours\" or \"Closest friends\" are examples.  

Letters of the alphabet cannot be interpreted as ordinal with respect to their use in words, since no uniform rules exist about their placement in words.  But they can be ordinal insofar as they are stated in a particular order in listing off the alphabet.

A distance metric becomes possible if the items have units, e.g. 5cm or 10degrees celcius.  The set's elements can then be mapped to one dimension."@en)
AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label obo:GENEPIO_0001901 "ordered set"@en)
SubClassOf(obo:GENEPIO_0001901 obo:GENEPIO_0001900)

# Class: obo:GENEPIO_0001902 (unordered set)

AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:comment obo:GENEPIO_0001902 "The set can have a very large or infinite (open-ended) number of values.  
Because the elements are essentially open-ended, we can only offer a lookup-as-you-type function for selecting past-used items.

Use \"Categorical\" for unordered sets where items are finite, pre-defined and not too numerous.

Strings are only indirectly ordered insofar as strings can be sorted by character - but this requires picking apar the name strings, an examination which has no inherent semantic relation to the things being named.  That one email address or name comes before another is arbitrary.  Only numbers are directly ordered."@en)
AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label obo:GENEPIO_0001902 "unordered set"@en)
SubClassOf(obo:GENEPIO_0001902 obo:GENEPIO_0001900)

# Class: obo:GENEPIO_0001903 (set of unordered strings)

AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:comment obo:GENEPIO_0001903 "Subclasses here are types of string that have a particular syntactic structure or constraint to them that should be expressable using regular expressions."@en)
AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label obo:GENEPIO_0001903 "set of unordered strings"@en)
SubClassOf(obo:GENEPIO_0001903 obo:GENEPIO_0001902)

# Class: obo:GENEPIO_0001904 (phone number (North America))

AnnotationAssertion(obo:GENEPIO_1919 obo:GENEPIO_0001904 "/^(:<area>(\\([0-9]{3})\\)|[0-9]{3})(:<sep>[- ])?(:<central>\\d{3})\\2(:<station>\\d{4})$/, $area $central $station")
AnnotationAssertion(obo:GENEPIO_1921 obo:GENEPIO_0001904 "($area) $central-$station")
AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label obo:GENEPIO_0001904 "phone number (North America)"@en)

# Class: obo:GENEPIO_0001905 (points in 2 dimensions)

AnnotationAssertion(obo:IAO_0000115 obo:GENEPIO_0001905 "A set of points that exist in a 2-dimensional plane. (This plane may be a cross-section of points defined in n > 2 dimensions)."@en)
